    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-VII-1-sols">
        <title><m>\S VII.1</m>: Taylor Polynomials</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Taylor Polynomials </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We've seen that differentiable functions look a lot like their tangent lines when we zoom in 
                            to a point. We can do even better with higher derivatives.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            See <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/alb2vb4jj8">the desmos interactive from class</url> for a visualization of this, as well 
                            as visuals of examples throughout this lesson.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Definition: Taylor Polynomial at <m>x=0</m></title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f</m> be a continuously differentiable function. The
                            <term><m>n^{th}</m> degree Taylor polynomial of <m>f</m> centered at <m>x=0</m></term> is
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                p_n(x)= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!} x^k
                            </me>.
                           The reason for these specific coefficients is that they force <m>p_n^{(k)}(0) = f^{(k)}(0)</m> 
                           for all <m>k</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Example: Taylor Polynomial</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x) = e^x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Then <m>p_4(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{6}x^3 + \frac{1}{24}x^4</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Note that this can be used to make very good approximations for <m>x</m>-values close to <m>0</m>:
                            <me>
                                e^{0.5} \approx p_4(0.5) = 1.6484375
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Practice: Taylor Polynomial</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>g(x) = \cos(x)</m>. Compute <m>p_4(x)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Note that <m>g'(0) = g'''(0) = 0</m>, so 
                            <me>
                                p_4(x)= 1 - \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{4!}x^4
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Definition: Taylor Polynomials with arbitrary center</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We can center Taylor polynomials at any <m>x</m>-value. Recall that the tangent line to <m>f</m>
                            at <m>x=a</m> is 
                            <me>
                                L(x)= f(a) +f'(a)(x-a)
                            </me>.
                            The <term><m>n^{th}</m> degree Taylor polynomial of <m>f</m> centered at <m>x=a</m> </term> is
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                p_n(x)= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{f^{(k)}(a)}{k!} (x-a)^k
                            </me>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Example: Taylor polynomial</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x) = e^x</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The fourth degree Taylor polynomial centered at <m>x=1</m> is 
                            <me>
                                p_4(x) = e + e(x-1) + \frac{e}{2}(x-1)^2 + \frac{e}{3!}(x-1)^3 + \frac{e}{4!}(x-1)^4
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Note that we can use this polynomial to make very good approximations for <m>x</m>-values close to
                            <m>1</m>:
                            <me>
                                e^{1.5} \approx p_4(1.5) \approx 4.4809177
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Taylor Polynomial</title>
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Compute the <m>2^{nd}</m> order Taylor polynomial of <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> centered at <m>x=1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Note that <m>f'(1) = 1</m> and <m>f''(1) = -1</m>, so 
                            <me>
                                p_2(x)= (x-1) - \frac{1}{2}(x-1)^2
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
            </page>

        </worksheet>
